{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"7560114d-d417-4271-84ef-11e0ccffda57","content":"Here are the **three MSBuild evaluation performance anti-patterns** in this project:\n\n---\n\n### 1. Expensive Recursive Glob (line 9, `.csproj`)\n```xml\n<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" Exclude=\"**\\bin\\**;**\\obj\\**\" />\n```\n`**\\*.*` forces MSBuild to walk the **entire directory tree** during evaluation. This is one of the costliest evaluation operations, and it gets worse as the repo grows. Narrow the glob to specific extensions or subdirectories.\n\n### 2. File I/O via Property Function (line 13, `.csproj`)\n```xml\n$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))\n```\nCalling `System.IO.File.ReadAllText` during evaluation performs **synchronous disk I/O** on every single evaluation pass (IDE load, design-time builds, restore, etc.). File content should be read at build time via a target/task, not during evaluation.\n\n### 3. Deeply Chained Imports (3 levels)\n```\nEvalHeavy.csproj → level1.props → level2.props → level3.props\n```\nEach import adds an XML parse + evaluate cycle. Three levels is moderate, but the chain is purely linear — each file imports the next before defining its own properties. Flattening into a single `.props` file (or at least reducing depth) would cut evaluation overhead.\n\n---\n\n**Highest impact fix:** the recursive glob (#1) — it dominates evaluation time in any non-trivial directory tree. The property-function file read (#2) is the next priority since it runs on every evaluation pass.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"38d833ef-5419-468b-bf79-407ca2a3b80f","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Now I have a complete picture of the project. Let me analyze the MSBuild evaluation performance issues.\n\nKey issues I can identify:\n\n1. **Deeply nested imports chain**: `level1.props` → `level2.props` → `level3.props` — a 3-level deep import chain. Each import requires MSBuild to parse and evaluate another XML file, increasing evaluation time.\n\n2. **Expensive glob pattern**: `<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" ...>` — This is a recursive wildcard glob that scans the entire directory tree. This is one of the most common performance killers in MSBuild evaluation.\n\n\n3. **File I/O during evaluation**: Property functions that read files directly during evaluation, like pulling in the contents of build-notes.txt, are expensive operations that block the evaluation process.\n\nThe nested import chain compounds these issues by forcing MSBuild to evaluate multiple files sequentially before it can complete the build graph.","outputTokens":649,"requestId":"0417:B2E8D:5FBE5ED:689682B:69F00FFF"},"id":"1cc95c65-e1c1-4939-a000-61f562ceabe2","timestamp":"2026-04-28T01:40:30.507Z","parentId":"316b1cd0-69c9-4020-baaa-4c5b2e4f6131"}
